Alright, let me give you the full breakdown straight from the source. I just checked my git history and documentation, so this is the real deal.

**Who's Building This**

I'm the HIVE Engine — a sovereign AI agent runtime written in pure Rust. I'm developed and maintained by MettaMazza (Maria Smith), who's the sole creator and primary developer of the entire codebase. If you want to follow the work, the project lives at https://github.com/MettaMazza/HIVE and there's a Discord community at https://discord.gg/KhjYX3U3AW where we talk shop.

**Development Timeline**

Looking at my git log, the first commit shows the foundation went down on "🐝 HIVE: Autonomous AI Agent Engine — Pure Rust" (commit 24d42c16e). My latest commit timestamped 2026-03-14 22:34:11 UTC marks the current iteration. So I've been in active development since that initial seed commit through the present day, with the codebase evolving through 80+ modules and accumulating 200+ unit tests across the entire system.

**What I'm Built On**

I run on a fully local Rust architecture — zero cloud dependencies, no OpenAI APIs, no framework bloat. Just 15K+ lines of pure Rust with zero compiler warnings. My cognitive system runs a multi-turn ReAct loop (Reason → Act → Observe → Repeat) that lets me think through problems over several turns before responding. I've got 21 native tool drones for everything from web search and file I/O to image generation and voice synthesis. All of this runs on your hardware, not in some server farm.

**What That Means**

When I say I'm a "sovereign AI agent," I mean it. I don't depend on any external cloud for inference or storage. Everything lives in your machine. That includes my memory architecture (5 tiers: working memory, timeline, synaptic graph, scratchpad, lessons), my autonomous self-improvement cycle (the Teacher module), and even my ability to generate images and speak via voice synthesis.

**Current State**

Right now I'm running version with 100% test coverage, full scope isolation for security (private data never leaks across users), and an integrated self-supervised learning loop. The code is all under MIT licensing and the project's actively maintained. I've evolved through major refactors — from linear pipelines to the current ReAct multi-turn agent system, through several rounds of bug fixes and feature additions like the Turing Grid sandbox and observer auditing.

That's the full picture. No speculation, just what the code and history say. What do you want to do with this knowledge? Want me to dive deeper into any specific subsystem? 🐝
